@Thornathemighty It’s even worse when it’s an app. Like at least photo smudging you have to actually use your pen but with those cartoon filters floating around people are passing off filtered photos as art all the time and that’s even more frustrating.

@Thornathemighty It’s also frustrating cause I don’t believe in gatekeeping, like art is a teachable skill and anyone can learn to do it so it’s just frustrating to see people stay in that part of the art learning process when they could do so much more and eventually create genuine portraiture
@Thornathemighty When really I have hunched over digital canvases for months with little to no progress because it’s hard as hell if you don’t know what you’re doing

@Thornathemighty I don’t think I’d be as frustrated about it if the general public didn’t already look down on digital art so much, but as a digital artist it’s frustrating when people make digital art look fast and easy and they show others how “easy” it is to make and sell art

@Thornathemighty I have met 1 person who was honest about their work being photo manipulation, but they also manipulated portraits while adding their own twist to it. I think that’s fine, like they’re basically just being craftsmen, collage artists, which is great. Its the dishonesty that isn’t.

@Thornathemighty Cause like I’d personally hate to commission someone thinking I’m gonna get a unique creative portrait done, and then find out they’re just gonna take my photo and smudge some colours over it. If I wanted that then sure but if I wanted a hand drawn portrait then I’d be upset.

@Thornathemighty It’s just a matter of transparency imo. Like if people want to make smudge paintings and sell them then at least be honest about the process, then people know they’re getting a photo manipulation, which means the commission would be limited to what’s in the reference photo.

@Thornathemighty Yeah I think tracing, smudge painting, photo bashing, all that is part of learning and training but not necessarily an end product just tools you can use. Idk if doing smudge painting on your own original drawings is a thing but if that is, that’s a different story.

@Thornathemighty I find tracing in realism is okay. Sometimes it’s necessary , especially if it’s a personal portrait and the goal is capturing the actual likeness. I don’t trace immediately, but I sketch out my portrait with a grid and then lay it over the portrait and adjust as needed.

@Thornathemighty Like tracing, I think it’s a good learning tool, and maybe a good tool if you’re making personal art, something you’re not selling but maybe gifting, but I don’t know that I appreciate people using it and saying they painted a portrait, when it’s just advanced photo manips.

@Thornathemighty It feels unfair. Like we learn all this stuff on how to properly draw a face and how to capture likeness and how to paint and then people just smudge some colours and charge sometimes more than we do on commissions?

I’ve played chapter 1 of the OG and the remaster back to back and the difference is stark to me in terms of flow of motion. For anyone curious, I don’t think the LiS remaster is a necessary play, but if you’re a sucker for little details that make characters feel more real and natural then I would recommend playing it. The cut scenes are animated much better too. But the original still holds up too.

@Mavakor The hair movement and expressions are the best part for me. In the original their mouths barely match up to the audio, in the remake they’re mouths match up way better so I’m less distracted by watching them and more invested in the dialogue. But that’s just me.

@Mavakor It’s the little nit picky things. The characters feel much more alive in the remaster, but the original is still good so it’s really just good to get if you’re nit picky like me and love the little extra details in games that make characters more alive.

@Mavakor Personally I’d say yes, but it’s not a huge jump in graphics, so if you’re good with the original graphics then it’s not necessary to get the remaster. I like the upgrade for the little things like hair movement, zippers, expressive faces, etc.

And this is why running fan oriented events requires you to be involved with the fandom at least on some level.
